Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Take the @British beef mince{250%g} out of the fridge ~{30%minutes} before cooking, if possible. Cut the @red onion{1.5} in half lengthways through the root. Then peel and slice the onions widthways very thinly into half moons.

Wash the @potato{1} but don't peel it. Chop the potato lengthways into wedges the thickness of a thumb (if you had chunky boxer's thumbs). Toss the wedges in @oil{2%tbsp}, lay them out in one layer spaced apart on a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle over @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good grind of @pepper{} and cook on the top shelf of the oven for ~{25%minutes} (until soft inside and brown on the outside).

Heat @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a #saucepan{} on low heat and add the onion with a pinch of salt and pepper. Add the @balsamic vinegar{2%tbsp}, place a #lid{} on the pan and gently cook for ~{20%minutes}, stirring once in a while.

Mix the beef mince in a #bowl{} with the @harissa paste{1} and just under @salt{1/2%tsp}. Form the beef into eight equal-sized burger patties.

> Tip: Don't press the meat together too firmly, as this will make the texture of the burger tough.

Heat @oil{2%tbsp} in a #nonstick frying pan{} on medium heat and once hot gently lay in your burgers. Cook for around ~{4%minutes} on each side and turn them only once. If you want to cook the burgers a little more in the middle, you can place them in the oven for a few minutes after frying.

Sandwich the burgers between some @wholemeal pita{2}; simply toast the pitas for a few minutes then split them in half.

> If you want to go pita free you can always freeze them for another meal.

Serve the burgers with a spoonful of red onions, a spoonful of @Greek style yoghurt{1/2}, the potato wedges and the @baby spinach{1%handful} leaves (we left our leaves undressed to balance against the richness of the burger).